<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-181-334  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 181 334.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 26 1990 v24 n9 p1(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Air system upgrade off course by $15B: FAA holding pattern. (part1)(includes related article on factors contributing to the FAA'sproblems) (Federal Aviation Administration's National AirspaceSystem)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Savage, J.A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>FAA officials will begin appearing before the AviationSubcommittee of the House of Representatives' Public WorksTransportation Committee to justify funding for the NationalAirspace System (NAS), the agency's computer modernization plan.andO;The plan, which had originally been approved in 1981, includes 12major systems acquisitions that would help handle congested airtraffic at major airports.andP;  Of those acquisitions, only one hasbeen implemented.andP;  According to critics, the systems are not inplace because of the FAA's poor contract management skills and itsresistance to hiring a primary contractor.andP;  The result of theseproblems has been a national air traffic control system that isyears late and $15 billion over an original $12 billion budget.andO;Other major components of the NAS include the Advanced AutomationSystem, which will provide controllers with updated trackingdisplays, and the installation of mainframe 'host' computers at 20control centers across the nation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Aviation AdministrationBudgetingAir Traffic ControlUpgradingMismanagementUnited States. General Accounting OfficeAir traffic controlSystem Design.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   National Airspace System cost additions. (table)Modernization costs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>